	"explanation1": {
		"component": "Explanation",
		"content": [
			"<p>In French there are several words that translate the word 'in'. If you are saying '<b>in</b>' <b>with a proper noun</b> i.e. a place name, you will see  à   en  au  aux   dans le . The chart below shows when each of these is used.</p><table><tbody><tr><td>à</td><td>Londres, Cambridge, Marseille</td><td>towns, cities, villages</td></tr><tr><td>à</td><td>Singapour, Hongkong, Taiwan</td><td>islands and archipelagos without gender</td></tr><tr><td>au</td><td>Maroc, Canada, Chili</td><td>masculine countries beginning with a consonant</td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>France, Suisse, Chine</td><td>all feminine countries</td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>Afghanistan, Iran, Andorre</td><td>masculine countries beginning with a vowel</td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>Provence, Nouvelle Calédonie</td><td>feminine provinces and regions </td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>Océanie, Afrique, Amérique du nord /du sud, Europe, Asie, Antarctique</td><td>the continents</td></tr><tr><td>aux</td><td>Pays Bas, Seychelles, États-Unis</td><td>plurals</td></tr><tr><td>dans le</td><td>Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Pas-de-Calais, Colorado</td><td>masculine provinces and regions including the British counties</td></tr></tbody></table>"
		],
		"id": "explanation1",
		"titleText": "Grammar / Use of Language"
	},
	"explanation2": {
		"component": "Explanation",
		"content": [
			"<p><b>How to pronounce:</b></p><p>another nasal vowel. This is the sound which is how the letters -in- are pronounced <b>when they end a word or occur before a consonant</b> as in these examples: <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/Singapour.mp3' alt='Singapour'/>Singapour</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/Inde.mp3' alt='Inde'>Inde</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/indien.mp3' alt='indien'>indien</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/Finlande.mp3' alt='Finlande'>Finlande</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/jardin.mp3' alt='jardin'>jardin</a>. The tongue and the mouth all have work to do in its production whilst air passes through nose and mouth.</p><p><b>NB</b> This is a useful sound to practise as the following are also pronounced in the same way <b>when they end a word or occur before a consonant:</b></p><p><b>ain</b>, <b>aim</b>, <b>ein</b>, <b>im</b>, <b>ym</b>, <b>yn</b>, <b>eim</b>.</p><p>Here are some examples of words containing the sound to practise:</p><p><a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/marocain.mp3' alt='marocain'>maroc<b>ain</b></a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/faim.mp3' alt='faim'>f<b>aim</b></a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/peinture.mp3' alt='peinture'>p<b>ein</b>ture</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/impossible.mp3' alt='impossible'><b>im</b>possible</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/symbole.mp3' alt='symbole'>s<b>ym</b>bole</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/lynx.mp3' alt='lynx'>l<b>yn</b>x</a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/Reims.mp3' alt='Reims'>R<b>eim</b>s</a>.</p><p>When the letters <b>en</b> or <b>ens</b> end a word this also pronounced (ain) </p><p><a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/australien.mp3' alt='australien'>australi<b>en</b></a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/européen.mp3' alt='européen'>europé<b>en</b></a>, <a  class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/ghanéens.mp3' alt='ghanéens'>ghané<b>ens</b></a>, <a class='sound-link' href='/sounds/fr/indiens.mp3' alt='indiens'>indi<b>ens</b></a>.</p>"
		],
		"id": "explanation2",
		"titleText": "Demystifying French Pronunciation"
	},
